===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|bad|lang=enm}}, {{term|badde||wicked, evil, depraved|lang=enm}}, of uncertain origin. Perhaps a shortening of {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|bæddel||hermaphrodite|lang=ang}} (for loss of ''-el'' compare Middle English {{term|muchel|lang=enm}} from {{etyl|ang|-}} {{m|ang|myċel}}, and Middle English {{m|enm|wenchel}} from Old English {{m|ang|wenċel}}), from {{term|bædan||to defile|lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*bad-}} (compare Old High German {{term|pad||hermaphrodite|lang=goh}}), from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*bʰoidʰ}}- (compare Welsh {{term|baedd||wild boar|lang=cy}}, Latin {{term|foedus||foul, filthy|lang=la}}, {{m|la|foedō||to defile, pollute}}). Alternatively, a loan from Old Norse into Middle English, compare Norwegian ''bad'' (neuter) "effort, trouble, fear", East Danish ''bad'' (neuter) "damage, destruction, fight", from the Proto-Germanic noun ''*bada-'' (Kroonen, ''Etymological Dictionary of Proto-Germanic'', s. v. ''*badōjan-'').

